    {
      "type": "concept",
      "title": "Two kinds of o",
      "thaiExample": "โก · กอ",
      "exampleAudioKey": "examples/ko_ko_ang",
      "body": [
        "Thai splits English \"o\" in two: โ◌ is the closed o of \"go\"; ◌อ is the open o of \"law\".",
        "Both have short forms that look bigger than they sound: โ◌ะ and เ◌าะ.",
        "Meet อ again: at the start of a word it silently carries a vowel, but written after a consonant it IS the vowel — long open o."
      ]
